---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const pageTitle = "Matthew Brunken - Runner, Fitness Enthusiast & Nebraska Native";
const pageDescription = "Discover the official website of Matthew Brunken, a dedicated runner and fitness professional based in Lincoln and Omaha, Nebraska. Follow his running journey, training insights, and community involvement across the Cornhusker State.";
---

<Layout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription}>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-content">
        <div class="hero-image">
          <img
            src="/images/profile.webp"
            alt="Matthew Brunken - Professional headshot photo taken in Nebraska"
            width="300"
            height="300"
            loading="eager"
            fetchpriority="high"
          />
        </div>
        <div class="hero-text">
          <h1>Matthew Brunken</h1>
          <p class="tagline">Runner. Fitness Enthusiast. Nebraska Native.</p>
          <p class="location">
            <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <path d="M21 10c0 7-9 13-9 13s-9-6-9-13a9 9 0 0 1 18 0z"/>
              <circle cx="12" cy="10" r="3"/>
            </svg>
            Lincoln & Omaha, Nebraska
          </p>
          <div class="hero-buttons">
            <a href="/about" class="btn btn-primary">Learn More About Matthew Brunken</a>
            <a href="/blog" class="btn btn-secondary">Read the Blog</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="intro">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="intro-content">
        <h2>Welcome to the Official Website of Matthew Brunken</h2>
        <p>Thank you for visiting the official website of Matthew Brunken, a passionate runner and fitness professional who calls the beautiful state of Nebraska home. Based between Lincoln and Omaha, Matthew has dedicated his life to the pursuit of fitness excellence and inspiring others to live healthier, more active lifestyles. Whether you're a seasoned runner, a fitness newcomer, or simply curious about the running culture in the Midwest, this website serves as your gateway to Matthew Brunken's world of running, training, and community engagement.</p>
        <p>Matthew Brunken's journey in athletics began at a young age, but his true passion for running emerged later in life, transforming not only his physical health but his entire approach to wellness. This transformation story resonates with countless individuals who find themselves seeking change and meaning through the simple act of putting one foot in front of the other. Today, Matthew shares his experiences, insights, and hard-won knowledge with a growing community of runners across Nebraska and beyond.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="about-matthew-brunken">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Who is Matthew Brunken?</h2>
      <p>Matthew Brunken represents a new generation of runners who understand that success isn't measured solely by race times or podium finishes, but by the positive impact one can have on others' lives. As a resident of Nebraska's two largest cities, Matthew has cultivated deep roots in both Lincoln and Omaha, drawing inspiration from the unique character and community spirit that define these Midwestern communities.</p>
      <p>The story of Matthew Brunken is one of transformation and perseverance. Like many who discover running later in life, he found in this sport something he hadn't known he was looking for: a way to challenge himself physically while finding mental clarity and emotional balance. What started as occasional jogs around his neighborhood has evolved into a lifelong commitment to the sport and all its associated benefits.</p>
      <p>Living in Nebraska presents unique opportunities and challenges for runners, and Matthew Brunken has embraced both. From the rolling hills surrounding Lincoln to the scenic riverfront trails of Omaha, the Cornhusker State offers diverse terrain for runners of all skill levels. Matthew has explored countless routes throughout the region, developing a deep appreciation for Nebraska's natural beauty and a keen understanding of how to train effectively in the state's variable climate.</p>

      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary>Read More About Matthew Brunken's Running Philosophy</summary>
        <p>Running, according to Matthew Brunken, is more than just exercise—it's a pathway to self-discovery and personal growth. His approach to the sport emphasizes consistency over intensity, patience over pressure, and enjoyment over perfection. This philosophy has guided his own running journey and shapes how he interacts with fellow runners in the community.</p>
        <p>Matthew believes that everyone has the potential to become a runner, regardless of age, fitness level, or previous athletic experience. He often speaks about the transformative power of setting achievable goals and celebrating small victories along the way. Whether someone wants to complete their first 5K or qualify for a major marathon, Matthew Brunken's philosophy centers on incremental progress and sustainable habits.</p>
        <p>Community plays a vital role in Matthew's running philosophy. He actively participates in group runs, local race events, and online running communities, always eager to share knowledge and encouragement with fellow runners. This commitment to community extends beyond just running—he volunteers with local organizations, supports youth fitness programs, and uses his social media platforms to promote health and wellness across Nebraska.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="locations">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Matthew Brunken's Nebraska: Lincoln and Omaha Running</h2>
      <p>Nebraska might not be the first state that comes to mind when you think of running culture, but Matthew Brunken is working to change that perception. The Cornhusker State offers an incredible environment for runners, with world-class facilities, supportive communities, and diverse terrain that rivals much larger states. Matthew splits his time between Lincoln and Omaha, the state's two largest cities, each offering distinct running experiences.</p>
      <p>Lincoln, Nebraska's capital city, provides an intimate running community where neighbors become training partners and local races draw participants from across the region. Matthew Brunken has established strong connections in Lincoln's running scene, regularly participating in group runs organized by local running stores and fitness clubs. The city's extensive trail system, including the popular Wilderness Ridge Trail and the Steve Kenny Memorial Trail, offers runners scenic routes through urban parks and natural areas.</p>

      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary>Explore Omaha Running with Matthew Brunken</summary>
        <p>Omaha, Nebraska's largest city, presents a different but equally compelling running environment. The Missouri River waterfront trails provide stunning views and flat, fast routes perfect for speed work and long runs alike. Matthew Brunken has explored virtually every running route Omaha has to offer, from the heart of downtown to the quieter suburban neighborhoods.</p>
        <p>The Omaha running community has embraced Matthew Brunken as one of its own, and he actively contributes to its growth and vitality. He regularly participates in events organized by the Omaha Running Club and other local organizations, using these opportunities to connect with fellow runners and share his experiences. The city's numerous running stores provide valuable resources for runners of all levels, and Matthew maintains relationships with these establishments to stay connected with the broader running community.</p>
        <p>Training in Nebraska requires adaptability, and Matthew Brunken has developed strategies for running in all four of the state's distinct seasons. Summer humidity, autumn winds, winter cold, and spring storms all present unique challenges that Nebraska runners must learn to navigate. Matthew shares these lessons through his blog and social media, helping others understand how to maintain consistent training throughout the year.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="community">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Matthew Brunken and the Nebraska Running Community</h2>
      <p>No runner succeeds alone, and Matthew Brunken credits much of his growth to the supportive running communities in Lincoln and Omaha. These communities include dedicated runners of all ages, abilities, and backgrounds, united by their shared passion for the sport. Matthew actively engages with these communities, participating in group runs, volunteering at local races, and mentoring newer runners who are just beginning their journeys.</p>
      <p>The running community in Nebraska extends beyond individual cities to encompass the entire state. Events like the Omaha Marathon, Lincoln Marathon, and numerous smaller races throughout the year create opportunities for runners to connect, compete, and celebrate their shared passion. Matthew Brunken can often be found at these events, whether participating as a runner, volunteering as crew, or simply cheering on fellow athletes from the sidelines.</p>

      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary>Social Running and Group Activities</summary>
        <p>Social media has become an essential tool for connecting runners, and Matthew Brunken maintains an active presence across multiple platforms. His Facebook profiles and Instagram account document his running journey, share training insights, and provide glimpses into the daily life of a dedicated Nebraska runner. These platforms have allowed Matthew to build relationships with runners from around the world while maintaining strong connections with his local Nebraska community.</p>
        <p>Running groups in Lincoln and Omaha welcome runners of all abilities, and Matthew encourages everyone to find their place in this supportive community. Whether you prefer early morning solo runs or Saturday morning group sessions, there's a place for you in Nebraska's running community. Matthew often organizes informal meetups and runs, creating opportunities for runners to connect and share their experiences in person.</p>
        <p>The benefits of community running extend far beyond physical fitness. Studies consistently show that exercising with others increases motivation, improves adherence to training programs, and enhances overall well-being. Matthew Brunken has experienced these benefits firsthand and is passionate about helping others discover the joy of running with friends and community members.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="training">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Training Insights from Matthew Brunken</h2>
      <p>Effective training requires more than just logging miles—it demands thoughtful planning, recovery management, and continuous learning. Matthew Brunken has developed his training approach through years of experimentation, education, and feedback from experienced coaches and fellow runners. While every runner's journey is unique, the principles Matthew follows have broad applicability for anyone seeking to improve their running.</p>
      <p>Matthew emphasizes the importance of building a strong aerobic base before adding intensity to training. This approach, often called "running slow to run fast," allows the body to adapt to the demands of running while minimizing injury risk. Many beginners make the mistake of running too fast too soon, leading to burnout or injury that derails their progress. Matthew's patient approach prioritizes long-term development over short-term gains.</p>

      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary>Training Through Nebraska's Seasons</summary>
        <p>Nebraska's climate presents unique training challenges that Matthew Brunken has learned to embrace. Summer heat and humidity require adjustments to pace, hydration, and timing of workouts. Early morning runs during summer months often provide the most comfortable conditions, while winter training demands attention to layering, visibility, and surface conditions. Spring and fall offer ideal running conditions but can bring sudden weather changes that require flexibility.</p>
        <p>Matthew uses the changing seasons as natural training phases, adjusting his goals and approaches to align with environmental conditions. Winter becomes a time for building aerobic fitness with lower-intensity running, while cooler months provide opportunities for higher-intensity workouts when conditions permit. This seasonal approach prevents monotony and helps maintain enthusiasm for running throughout the year.</p>
        <p>Trail running has become an important component of Matthew Brunken's training regimen, offering variety from road running and reducing the repetitive stress that can lead to injury. Nebraska's state parks and natural areas provide excellent trail running opportunities, and Matthew explores these routes regularly, discovering new challenges and enjoying the mental refresh that comes from running in nature.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="features">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Connect with Matthew Brunken</h2>
      <p>Matthew Brunken maintains an active presence across multiple social media platforms, using these channels to share his running journey, training insights, and life experiences in Nebraska. Connecting with Matthew online provides opportunities to learn from his experiences, get answers to your running questions, and become part of a supportive community of runners.</p>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <div class="feature-card">
          <svg width="32" height="32" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor"><path d="M18 2h-3a5 5 0 0 0-5 5v3H7v4h3v8h4v-8h3l1-4h-4V7a1 1 0 0 1 1-1h3z"/></svg>
          <h3>Facebook</h3>
          <p>Follow Matthew Brunken on Facebook for daily updates, training tips, and running insights from Nebraska.</p>
          <a href="https://www.facebook.com/matthew.brunken" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Connect on Facebook</a>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <svg width="32" height="32" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><rect x="2" y="2" width="20" height="20" rx="5" ry="5"/><path d="M16 11.37A4 4 0 1 1 12.63 8 4 4 0 0 1 16 11.37z"/><line x1="17.5" y1="6.5" x2="17.51" y2="6.5"/></svg>
          <h3>Instagram</h3>
          <p>See running photos, race recaps, and behind-the-scenes content on Matthew Brunken's Instagram.</p>
          <a href="https://www.instagram.com/brunkenmalex/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Follow on Instagram</a>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <svg width="32" height="32" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor"><path d="M18.244 2.25h3.308l-7.227 8.26 8.502 11.24H16.17l-5.214-6.817L4.99 21.75H1.68l7.73-8.835L1.254 2.25H8.08l4.713 6.231zm-1.161 17.52h1.833L7.084 4.126H5.117z"/></svg>
          <h3>X (Twitter)</h3>
          <p>Join the conversation and get real-time updates from Matthew Brunken on X.</p>
          <a href="https://x.com/matthew_brunken" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Follow on X</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="blog-preview">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Latest from Matthew Brunken's Blog</h2>
      <p>Matthew Brunken writes regularly about running, training, and life as a Nebraska runner. The blog covers topics ranging from practical training advice to reflections on the mental aspects of the sport. Whether you're looking for tips on starting your running journey or insights into advanced training techniques, you'll find valuable content written from real-world experience.</p>
      <div class="blog-grid">
        <article class="blog-card">
          <h3>Starting Your Running Journey: A Beginner's Guide</h3>
          <p>Essential advice for beginners looking to start their running journey in Nebraska's diverse landscapes.</p>
          <a href="/blog/starting-your-running-journey" class="read-more">Read More</a>
        </article>
        <article class="blog-card">
          <h3>Training Through Nebraska's Four Seasons</h3>
          <p>How Matthew Brunken adapts his training to the changing weather conditions across Lincoln and Omaha.</p>
          <a href="/blog/training-through-nebraska-seasons" class="read-more">Read More</a>
        </article>
        <article class="blog-card">
          <h3>The Running Community in Lincoln and Omaha</h3>
          <p>Exploring the vibrant running communities and discovering the best group runs in Nebraska's cities.</p>
          <a href="/blog/running-community-lincoln-omaha" class="read-more">Read More</a>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cta">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Get in Touch with Matthew Brunken</h2>
      <p>Have questions about running, training, or life as a Nebraska runner? Matthew Brunken welcomes inquiries from fellow runners, fitness enthusiasts, and anyone interested in learning more about the running lifestyle. Reach out to connect, collaborate, or simply say hello.</p>
      <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-primary">Contact Matthew Brunken</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .hero {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, #eff6ff 0%, #dbeafe 100%);
    padding: 4rem 0;
  }

  .hero-content {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: auto 1fr;
    gap: 3rem;
    align-items: center;
  }

  .hero-image img {
    width: 300px;
    height: 300px;
    object-fit: cover;
    border-radius: 50%;
    box-shadow: 0 20px 40px rgba(0,0,0,0.15);
    border: 4px solid white;
  }

  .hero-text h1 {
    font-size: 2.5rem;
    color: #1e3a5f;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .tagline {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    color: #4b5563;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .location {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    color: #6b7280;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .hero-buttons {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .intro, .about-matthew-brunken, .locations, .community, .training {
    padding: 3rem 0;
    background: white;
  }

  .intro h2, .about-matthew-brunken h2, .locations h2, .community h2, .training h2 {
    font-size: 1.75rem;
    color: #1e3a5f;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .intro-content p, .about-matthew-brunken > p, .locations > p, .community > p, .training > p {
    color: #4b5563;
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    max-width: 800px;
  }

  .collapsible {
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
    background: #f9fafb;
    border-radius: 0.5rem;
    padding: 1rem 1.5rem;
    border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;
  }

  .collapsible summary {
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #2563eb;
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    padding-right: 1.5rem;
    position: relative;
  }

  .collapsible summary::after {
    content: "+";
    position: absolute;
    right: 0;
    font-weight: bold;
  }

  .collapsible[open] summary::after {
    content: "-";
  }

  .collapsible summary::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .collapsible p {
    color: #4b5563;
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin-top: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .features {
    padding: 4rem 0;
    background: #f9fafb;
  }

  .features h2 {
    text-align: center;
    font-size: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    color: #1e3a5f;
  }

  .feature-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr));
    gap: 2rem;
  }

  .feature-card {
    text-align: center;
    padding: 2rem;
    border-radius: 1rem;
    background: white;
    border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;
    transition: transform 0.2s, box-shadow 0.2s;
  }

  .feature-card:hover {
    transform: translateY(-4px);
    box-shadow: 0 10px 30px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
  }

  .feature-card svg {
    color: #2563eb;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .feature-card h3 {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    color: #1e3a5f;
  }

  .feature-card p {
    color: #6b7280;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .feature-card a {
    color: #2563eb;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .blog-preview {
    padding: 4rem 0;
    background: white;
  }

  .blog-preview h2 {
    text-align: center;
    font-size: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    color: #1e3a5f;
  }

  .blog-preview > .container > p {
    text-align: center;
    max-width: 700px;
    margin: 0 auto 2rem;
    color: #6b7280;
  }

  .blog-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(300px, 1fr));
    gap: 2rem;
  }

  .blog-card {
    background: #f9fafb;
    padding: 2rem;
    border-radius: 1rem;
    box-shadow: 0 4px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.05);
    border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;
  }

  .blog-card h3 {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    color: #1e3a5f;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .blog-card p {
    color: #6b7280;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .read-more {
    color: #2563eb;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .cta {
    padding: 4rem 0;
    text-align: center;
    background: #1e3a5f;
    color: white;
  }

  .cta h2 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .cta p {
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: 0 auto 1.5rem;
    opacity: 0.9;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .btn-primary {
    background-color: #2563eb;
    color: white;
  }

  .btn-secondary {
    background-color: white;
    color: #2563eb;
    border: 2px solid #2563eb;
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .hero-content {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      text-align: center;
    }

    .hero-image {
      justify-self: center;
    }

    .hero-image img {
      width: 200px;
      height: 200px;
    }

    .hero-buttons {
      justify-content: center;
    }

    .location {
      justify-content: center;
    }
  }
</style>
